description: Socketed looped spearhead; socket round at mouth, developing into lozenge shaped midrib running down to point; edges of blade damaged (broken and turned over in places). Socket partly split at base of blade, the split running partly up on to the midrib. Prominent (?) ridges at sides of socket.
remarks: Sent to B.M. 1937, by Mrs. Carson. In a letter 28.5.38 she says she has now interviewed the workman who found it, and his statement is that he found it "about 8 years ago (i.e. c. 1930) in the bed of the R. Meon where the Titchfield-Stubbington road crosses it " when "excavating for the foundations of a small road-bridge"; he "came upon it about 4 feet below the surface of the river bed, a few feet from the downstream side of the bridge." This bridge is in Titchfield Parish, the bridge being in fact at the end of Bridge Street, Titchfield, which continues across it as the road to Stubbington.

surface: Smooth and in fairly good condition
description: Spearhead in very bent and poor condition. The metal is very thin and is evidently a bungled casting; edges and point sharp. Upper end of blade bent over, and cracked across one face about 1" from the point; edges rather chipped and bent over, but very sharp; crack across one face where the blade joins the socket (on the opposite face from the crack) near the point; the socket is bent below this crack, in the opposite direction from the bend near the point, the whole spearhead being 'S' shaped in profile; loops are not broken, but are imperfect castings. Mouth of socket damaged, and of thin metal.

patina: Bright green patina and some dark brown
surface: Fairly smooth. The blade more than the shaft is marked and grained in lines longitudinally. Also there are transverse hair-like lines on one aide along the summit of midrib and surrounding the whole shank.
description: Conical socket. Very flat wings of even thickness and very narrow slight bevel. Blade broken and cracked in one place. Two rivet holes in same plane as blade. There is a ridge extending along the seams of the casting which gives a keel like appearance to the sides of the shank. A simple zigzag double line in each of the angles between the wings and the blade.
publications: Prehistoric Bronzes, 154. No catalogue.,Foster Bequest, 281. The numbers do not correspond in the catalogue.
